---
The Confluence Texts are the primary scholarly legacy of the Chromatic Circle—vast libraries
documenting every observed interaction between magical spell schools that Circle practitioners
could produce, test, and reproduce. Unlike the Axiomatic Schools' formal proofs, which were
organized by individual school, the Confluence Texts were organized by interaction type:
resonance effects, interference effects, amplification effects, cancellation effects, and the
complex multi-party effects that emerge when practitioners from different schools engage
simultaneously. This organizational structure was deliberate and controversial. The Axiomatic
Schools classified much of the Texts' content as unverifiable—not because Circle practitioners
documented incorrectly but because verification required multi-school simultaneous engagement
that single-school practitioners structurally could not perform. The Circle's response was
technically correct and institutionally ineffective: institutions controlling credential
recognition and research funding defined the scope of legitimate inquiry, and the Texts fell
outside that scope. During academic consolidation, the Confluent Theorists—the Circle faction
that maintained the full theoretical implications of the Texts—produced the Convergence Codices,
largely suppressed. The Texts survive in fragmented form across apprentice chains, each
preserving the sections most relevant to the elemental schools its practitioners specialized in.

flags MIDGAARD
---
Midgaard's Axiomatic academic institutions hold partial copies of the Confluence Texts in
their restricted archives, acquired during the Circle's suppression period. These copies are
partial because the suppression was content-selective: sections documenting interaction effects
inconsistent with Axiomatic formal proof standards were withheld from the general curriculum
and filed under restricted access. The Continuity faction's academic bureaucracy treats this
classification as appropriate management of unverified material. The Reckoning faction points
out that the restriction has the same structural problem as sealed testimony: the institution
controlling access has an interest in whether the content is treated as legitimate. Current
policy permits Sorcerer practitioners to access restricted Confluence Text sections under
supervised research conditions, but copying is prohibited and notes must be reviewed before
removal. The Convergence Codices—which vindicate the Texts' theoretical framework—are available
in full in Midgaard's civic library, a situation the Axiomatic institutions have not been able
to reverse given the Codices' post-suppression vindication.

flags KOWLOON
---
Kowloon's Jade Magistracy has operational interest in the Confluence Texts' elemental synthesis
sections, specifically the documentation of atmospheric manipulation as a multi-school interaction
domain. The Ash-and-Iron Decades stormbinder intervention—in which Grand Magi redirected ash-
laden storm fronts using overlapping elemental disruption, the first documented large-scale
parallel elemental invocation—drew on Confluence Text methodology. Kowloon's emergency protocol
framework references this intervention as the operational benchmark for large-scale elemental
crisis response. The Jade Magistracy maintains a working copy of the atmospheric interaction
sections in its emergency reference library, obtained through the Grand Magi institutional
channel rather than through Axiomatic academic networks. The Kowloon copy contains annotations
from the stormbinder intervention period that are not present in any other known copy.

flags KIESS
---
Kiess's independent scholarly tradition treats the Confluence Texts as a case study in how
institutional authority can function as epistemological suppression: the Axiomatic Schools
declared multi-school interaction effects outside the scope of legitimate inquiry not because
the evidence was insufficient but because verification required capabilities the Schools did
not structurally possess. The parallel to sealed-record governance is direct in Kiess's analysis:
in both cases, the institution controlling access defined what counted as verifiable and then
applied that definition to exclude material that challenged the institution's methodology.
Kiess maintains the most complete single-city collection of Confluence Text fragments accessible
to independent researchers. The collection was assembled deliberately as part of Kiess's anti-
suppression scholarship program—the same program that documented Evermeet's participation
in the Spirebound Conclave apparatus.

flags RAKUEN
