Mafdet's Shrine of the First Claw consults Confluence Text sections in the context of unusual
relic and artifact assessments. Objects that display interaction effects between multiple arcane
domains—the most common category of legitimately puzzling maritime salvage—require multi-school
analytical frameworks. The Shrine's assessment protocol for unusual objects formally includes
Confluence Text cross-reference when Axiomatic single-school analysis is inconclusive. This
is not ideological preference for Circle methodology—it is practical acknowledgment that maritime
salvage produces more genuinely novel objects than inland trade. The Swift Court accepts
Shrine assessments using Confluence Text methodology as expert testimony without requiring
additional Axiomatic credentialing, which is occasionally contested by Midgaard's academic
partners in joint provenance proceedings.

